ana Cavarero, and Lea Melandri. In addition, the essays extend the conversation beyond the realm of Italian philosophy, bringing its thinkers into dialogue with philosophical figures including Badiou, Marx, Merleau-Ponty, Deleuze and Guattari, Adorno, Arendt, Foucault, Wittgenstein, and the Peruvian historian and sociologist Anibal Quijano.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPolitical sciencexHistoryx21st centuryxItalyxItaly. 0aPolitical sciencezItalyxHistoryy21st century. 4aArea Studies : Italian Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Continental Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Philosophy. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Theory. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aBerardi, Franco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBertland, Alexander U., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalcagno, Antonio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalcagno, Antonio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCarrera, Alessandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsposito, Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGenosko, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamarche, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLopes, Ricardo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLotz, Christian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMelchiori, Paola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMurphy, Timothy S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRago, Margareth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoncalli, Elvira, 